06724nam a22008775i 9781400866717DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20142001nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008667177 a10.1515/97814008667172doi  a(DE-B1597)459752  a(OCoLC)979580047  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aMUS0280002bisacsh04a782.100aSiren Songs :bRepresentations of Gender and Sexuality in Opera /ced. by Mary Ann Smart. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2014] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b32 illus, 7 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in Opera ;v3400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThrough Voices, History -- tThe Absent Mother in Opera Seria -- tStaging Mozart's Women -- tThe Career of Cherubino, or the Trouser Role Grows Up -- tElisabeth's Last Act -- tBody and Voice in Melodrama and Opera -- tUlterior Motives: Verdi's Recurring Themes Revisited -- tMelisande's Hair, or the Trouble in Allemande: A Postmodern Allegory at the Opera-Comique -- tOpera: Two or Three Things I Know about Her -- tStaging the Female Body: Richard Strauss's Salome -- t"Soulless Machines" and Steppenwolves: Renegotiating Masculinity in Krenek's Jonny spielt auf -- t"Grimes Is at His Exercise": Sex, Politics, and Violence in the Librettos of Peter Grimes -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt has long been argued that opera is all about sex. Siren Songs is the first collection of articles devoted to exploring the impact of this sexual obsession, and of the power relations that come with it, on the music, words, and staging of opera. Here a distinguished and diverse group of musicologists, literary critics, and feminist scholars address a wide range of fascinating topics--from Salome's striptease to hysteria to jazz and gender--in Italian, English, German, and French operas from the eighteenth to the twentieth centuries. The authors combine readings of specific scenes with efforts to situate these musical moments within richly and precisely observed historical contexts. Challenging both formalist categories of musical analysis and the rhetoric that traditionally pits a male composer against the female characters he creates, many of the articles work toward inventing a language for the study of gender and opera. The collection opens with Mary Ann Smart's introduction, which provides an engaging reflection on the state of gender topics in operatic criticism and musicology. It then moves on to a foundational essay on the complex relationships between opera and history by the renowned philosopher and novelist Catherine Clément, a pioneer of feminist opera criticism. Other articles examine the evolution of the "trouser role" as it evolved in the lesbian subculture of fin-de-siècle Paris, the phenomenon of opera seria's "absent mother" as a manifestation of attitudes to the family under absolutism, the invention of a "hystericized voice" in Verdi's Don Carlos, and a collaborative discussion of the staging problems posed by the gender politics of Mozart's operas. The contributors are Wye Jamison Allanboork, Joseph Auner, Katherine Bergeron, Philip Brett, Peter Brooks, Catherine Clement, Martha Feldman, Heather Hadlock, Mary Hunter, Linda Hutcheon and Michael Hutcheon, M.D., Lawrence Kramer, Roger Parker, Mary Ann Smart, and Gretchen Wheelock.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aFeminism and musicvCongresses. 0aSex in operavCongresses. 0aWomen in operavCongresses. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Opera.2bisacsh1 aAllanbrook, Wye Jamison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAuner, Joseph Henry, econtributor.4ctb